          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823443?width=860&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ina Jang，《华尔街日报》 </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0000981788"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 10:56 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/have-we-ruined-sex-241c57eb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p class="has-drop-cap"><strong>凯蒂·罗伊夫</strong>说，我们不应该为了意识形态的一致性而监管我们的性生活。<strong>安德鲁·沙利文（Andrew Sullivan）</strong>记得他的性觉醒是在互联网和约会应用程序出现之前的时代。<strong>玛丽·哈林顿</strong>解释了为什么我们更多地谈论性，却很少享受性。<strong>科尔曼休斯</strong>问谁真正受益于“勾搭文化”。<strong>艾格尼丝·卡拉德</strong>探索了哲学可以教会我们什么关于欲望的价值。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3><strong>回到逃脱、玩耍和冒险</strong></h3><p><em>凯蒂·罗伊夫</em><br><br>如果一个女人幻想着被一个男人压倒，她是不是在上演父权剧本的替罪羊？她是过去所谓的“错误意识”的受害者吗？正如格洛丽亚·斯泰纳姆（Gloria Steinem）曾经说过的那样，某些女权主义亚文化长期以来一直相信，我们可以以某种方式“理清性和攻击性”。半个世纪前，琼·迪迪恩（Joan Didion）令人难忘地嘲笑了围绕“性关系的‘温柔’”的女权主义愿望，就好像参与者是受伤的小鸟一样。</p><p>如今，我们教室内外的谈话似乎都朝着同一个方向发展。杰出的女权主义哲学家阿米亚·斯里尼瓦桑（Amia Srinivasan）问道：“是否有责任尽我们所能地改变我们的欲望”，她提出了一个非常聪明而细致的案例。在她大学性哲学课程的一篇论文中，我女儿最近引用了女权主义学者桑德拉·巴特基（Sandra Bartky）的话：“对欲望的彻底改革显然已列入女权主义议程：我们应该用瑞德·巴特勒（Rhett Butler）压垮的幻想来换取一个。”我们夺取国家政权并重新教育他。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span>绝对一致性和遵守清单的愿望的想法是有缺陷的。 <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p>女权主义者在喝了几杯玛格丽塔酒后“对瑞德·巴特勒进行再教育”的形象显然近乎模仿——更不用说“再教育”这个词还带有令人毛骨悚然的独裁色彩。但我们能够以某种方式监管我们的性行为以实现政治一致性的幻想比人们想象的更为普遍，甚至成为主流。</p><p>从这种话语中浮现出一种微弱的理想，即每个人在最亲密的环境中都友善、明智、完全受控、完全尊重和平等。但在我看来，这种绝对一致性的理想存在一些缺陷和净化，这种理想遵循我们有意识的头脑尽职尽责地收集的清单。这个形象忽视了一个不方便的现实，即对于许多人来说，性涉及矛盾、逃避、游戏、风险、实验、戏剧。性的吸引力恰恰在于人们不必在白天表现得令人尊敬。亲密领域逃避了，也许应该逃避，我们试图用政治信念或对父权制的厌恶之类的东西来规范它们。</p><p>有一种另类的女权主义传统承认并接受亲密生活的纠缠和复杂性——我们在权力和欲望方面是多么分裂和冲突。当西蒙娜·德·波伏娃被问及她对终身伴侣让-保罗·萨特的浪漫征服是否与她的女权主义政治相矛盾时，她说：“好吧，我不在乎……我很抱歉让女权主义者失望，但是太糟糕了，他们中的许多人只生活在理论中，而不是现实生活中。”许多年后，克里斯·克劳斯在她颇具影响力的小说《我爱迪克》中写道：“我是一个受虐狂吗？我告诉他，“不，”因为你没看到吗？发生在我身上的一切都只是因为我愿意。”</p><p><em>凯蒂·罗伊夫 (Katie Roiphe) 是纽约大学文化报道和批评项目的主任，也是最近出版的《权力笔记本》一书的作者。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="956" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823448?width=700&amp;height=956" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ina Jang，《华尔街日报》</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3><strong>神秘感的丧失，无论好坏</strong></h3><p><em>安德鲁·沙利文</em></p><p>当我的荷尔蒙第一次发挥作用时，我完全蒙在鼓里。在接下来的10年里，我的性生活完全是我一个人。那是 20 世纪 70 年代，我无法接触到色情作品，甚至完全不知道自己会和另一个男人做什么，也没有任何关于同性恋的参考。</p><p>但我有我的想象力和一本素描本，我会在里面画出男人的形象。他们在某种程度上很卡通——大方的下巴和肩膀，巨大的胸部覆盖着浓密的黑毛。偶尔，周日报纸杂志上会刊登一些广告，广告中的男性都脱掉了衬衫，现在我可以闭上眼睛，看到一篇特别的社论时尚专题，其中有赤裸上身、穿着平角短裤的拳击手的照片。我把它们剪下来并粘在我的书上。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span>当我今天遇到年轻的男同性恋者时，他们已经知道一切了。 <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p>当我第一次鼓起勇气去触碰另一个男人时，一切都是新的、不成熟的：胡茬、气味、体毛的感觉。只是这种亲密感本身就让我震惊。在那些日子里，还有奇怪的、精心设计的街头巡游舞蹈，吸引某人的目光，并且时不时地退回公寓。</p><p>当我今天遇到年轻的男同性恋者时，他们已经知道一切了。他们看过所有能想象到的色情电影。他们知道每一种可以想到的性爱姿势，并养成了相关的习惯；他们有复杂的恋物癖；他们见到的第一批男人出现在银幕上。我被迫创造自己的幻想；他们通过手机和笔记本电脑被动地接收信息，是预先包装好的、临床的、无情的、冷酷的。</p><p>几乎没有街道巡游；只是低着头不断检查应用程序。没有什么秘密。如果你在网上联系，你很可能会看到你即将见到的身体的每一寸，以及尺寸和精确的偏好。过去所有的沮丧和兴奋都被简化为点击屏幕的几秒钟。随时随地做爱从未如此简单，也从未如此无聊。</p><p>我不想神话化过去。在 20 世纪 60 年代和 70 年代，同性恋成长在很多方面都是残酷的。严格来说，直到 20 世纪 90 年代，在我自己的公寓里发生性行为都是违法的。因为艾滋病，在我性生活的头十年里，死亡徘徊在边缘，随时准备扑向我。由于艾滋病毒进入了我的血液，性生活中充满了拒绝和残忍，以及与其他艾滋病毒感染者的激烈程度，这是未来任何人都无法理解的。</p><p>这一切充满了黑暗，还有一种今天的年轻男同性恋者永远不会体验到的令人心旷神怡的兴奋。我希望他们永远不会。但那里有一些东西，一些可怕而重要的东西，我将永远记住。</p><p><em>安德鲁·沙利文撰写时事通讯“每周菜肴”。他是《孤立无援：写作精选，1989-2021》一书的作者。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3><strong>收回镇压的力量</strong></h3><p><em>玛丽·哈灵顿</em></p><p>有性生殖是我们最自然、最根本的动力之一，所以我怀疑我们是否能够完全“毁掉”它。但对于人类来说，没有什么是自然而然的。这也是文化的。就性文化而言，我们遇到了麻烦。旨在让我们更加自由、更加感性的性革命，在实践中却产生了相反的效果。<br><br>尽管“性革命”一词与摇摆的六十年代有关，但它是由精神分析学家威廉·赖克（Wilhelm Reich）在三十年前创造的。赖克挑战了弗洛伊德关于压抑对文明至关重要的观点，他认为乌托邦可以通过解放人类的性欲来实现。虽然他在 20 世纪 30 年代是一个边缘人物，但后来在美国反主流文化中找到了一群狂热的听众，他们热切地接受了他的信念，即性抑制是法西斯主义的驱动力。<br><br>自 20 世纪 60 年代以来，进步的美国开始倾向于美国的解放呼声。但迄今为止，这还没有产生赖希所设想的感性的社会主义乌托邦。相反，将爱欲从压抑的束缚中解放出来的最大受益者是企业家阶层。性解放的时代同时也是花花公子俱乐部和蓬勃发展的色情产业的时代，这并非巧合。<br><br>半个世纪过去了，革命者现在成了当权者。性产业复合体渗透到文化的各个方面，智能手机为每个消费者提供了无限量的约会资料和免费观看的色情内容。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为我们对性的看法最重要的变化是什么？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>但由此产生的性文化热吗？这是不言而喻的。近年来的大量报告表明，美国人的性行为不是更多，而是更少。而且这种情况似乎随着每一代人的发展而变得越来越糟。<br><br>资深性专栏作家玛丽亚·亚戈达在最近的一本书中指出，这并不是因为我们对性的讨论还不够。年轻人在性话语的熏陶下长大，善于从理智上分析和构建自己的性身份。但这是以牺牲真正享受性为代价的，性越自觉地带有商业、政治或身份主义的意义，性就越不那么直接令人愉悦。<br><br>对性开放的追求非但没有让世界变得更自由、更感性，反而削弱了快感。逃离国家规定的性产业复合体并不意味着解放，而是意味着克制。不再公开庆祝性行为；更多私人乐趣。不再开放；更加亲密。通过邮件发送手写的色情短信，或者什么也不发送。在 21 世纪，要真正对性持积极态度，就意味着收回压抑的力量。<br><br><em>玛丽·哈林顿 (Mary Harrington) 是 UnHerd 的特约编辑，也是《女权主义反对进步》一书的作者。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="992" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-823453?width=700&amp;height=992" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ina Jang，《华尔街日报》</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3><strong>联播文化及其不满</strong></h3><p><em>作者</em>：科尔曼·休斯<br></p><p>2016 年至 2020 年，当我在哥伦比亚大学读本科时，我经常讨论所谓的“勾搭文化”。粗略地说，这种想法是，在没有任何关系或承诺的情况下发生性行为是正常的、好的，而且确实是进步的。</p><p>年轻人不需要太多说服力。勾搭文化与我们的“工厂环境”非常吻合，以至于一群男性朋友几乎不会想到讨论这个问题。一群大学男生讨论勾搭文化，就像一群老派牛仔自发地讨论枪支文化的优点一样。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span>通常只需要一次可怕的、没有承诺的勾搭就能让女人知道这种规范出了问题。 <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p>事实上，年轻女性对勾搭文化有自己的看法——在某些情况下持支持态度，在另一些情况下则持消极态度。当年轻女性反对时，通常有一个简单的理由：经验。通常只需要与一个年轻人进行一次可怕的、没有承诺的勾搭，及其心理后果，就能让她知道这种规范出了问题。</p><p>更让我惊讶的是那些支持勾搭文化的年轻女性。对他们来说，勾搭文化有一个不同的名字：“性积极性”。她们将性积极性视为女权主义对父权正统观念的一种反抗，这种正统观念因女性进行无承诺的性行为而羞辱女性，而男性也有同样行为的通行证。她们往往不喜欢男人，尤其是异性恋白人。</p><p>具有讽刺意味的是，勾搭文化的最大受益者正是他们声称不喜欢的男人。那些人自然不反对。他们非常喜欢参与其中。但他们也没有太过口头支持，以免哪个性别真正受益变得显而易见。总的来说，当女人们互相讨论这个问题时，年轻男人很乐意站在一边。</p><p>我怀疑，2010年代这么多年轻女性对大学校园性侵犯产生的道德恐慌的部分原因是——当时政客和媒体人物经常重复错误的说法，即五分之一的大学女性有性侵犯行为。受到攻击——是因为他们中的许多人对勾搭文化产生的针对年轻人的愤怒感到愤怒。</p><p>换句话说，真正的问题不是校园性侵犯的战区水平。真正的问题是一种文化，它不仅批准而且鼓励年轻人发生性行为，而不期望有任何礼貌、后续行动或承诺——尤其是男性方面。虽然她们不能因为年轻男性参与勾搭文化而生气，这被认为是一种女权主义和进步的创新，但女性可以在性侵犯问题上将愤怒发泄到年轻男性身上。</p><p>如果年轻男女想要对性和人际关系形成健康的态度，就必须诚实地讨论勾搭文化。在否认过去的父权制规范时，我们不应该在另一个方向上走得太远，以至于最终伤害了女权主义革命本应帮助的人们。</p><p><br><em>科尔曼·休斯 (Coleman Hughes) 是美国有线电视新闻网 (CNN) 的政治分析师、《自由报》的特约撰稿人以及“与科尔曼对话”播客的主持人。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3><strong>同意的平坦性</strong></h3><p><em>艾格尼丝·卡拉德</em><br><br>我们对性了解多少？看到就知道，做了就知道，知道它的意义。但当需要说明其重要性时，我们就不太确定了。我们所知道和不知道的这种模式暗示了“性是什么？”这个问题的答案。性是一种仪式。<br><br>仪式是象征性地实现一个想法的一系列行为。握手或鞠躬表达了相互认可的意思；婚礼标志着承诺的实现。对于我们难以直接表达的想法，我们往往最需要这些符号。例如，我们对死亡的想法有困难，有时会对所爱的人说：“我不敢相信她死了。”葬礼传达了这样的想法：“她不仅没有在这个或那个场合失踪；她还没有失踪。”她已经永远消失了。”睡前仪式，比如讲故事和晚安之吻，传达了这样的想法：“我仍然关心你，尽管我让你独自一人在黑暗中无所事事”——而且它比简单地说这些要好字。<br><br>性所产生的观念是最棘手的观念之一：彻底的互惠欲望。亚里士多德要求我们想象两个恋人之间的选择：第一个非常想与你发生性关系，但不能，而第二个可以并且愿意，但并不真正喜欢。亚里士多德说，如果你是一个真正好色的人，你会选择第一个。欲望之所以具有情欲，是因为它只需得到回报就能得到满足。<br><br>我可以以各种方式想要你——竞选总统、作为桥梁伙伴等等——但是当我以这种方式想要你时，我所想要的就是你以完全相同的方式想要我，那么我的欲望是性的。非性欲可能会寻求回报，但不仅仅是回报。如果我想让你和我一起去散步，你并不能通过想要和我一起去散步来满足这个愿望——因为真正的散步呢？仅仅通过反映在另一个欲望中就能满足的欲望是一种奇怪的欲望，奇怪的是我们不是直接表达这种欲望的想法，而是通过仪式的方式来实现它。性就是那种仪式。<br><br>同意的想法，或者持续的同意，或者持续的热情同意——这些都是互惠欲望的三维概念的二维投影。这就是为什么当试图捕捉性、仪式的含义时，同意感觉平淡或薄弱。我们不应感到惊讶的是，同意仅限于可以直接、非象征性表达的范围（你必须能够具体说明你同意什么），无法传达相关的想法。为了传达这个想法，我们发生了性行为。<br><br><em>艾格尼丝·卡拉德是芝加哥大学哲学教授。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/have-we-ruined-sex-241c57eb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/have-we-ruined-sex-241c57eb<category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>色情</category><category>社会问题</category><category>性别平等</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>色情</category><category>社会问题</category><category>性别平等</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Enjoy Alcohol, Without the Hangover]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>科学家们正在寻找帮助人们更快清醒并减少不良影响的方法<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819420/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Daisy korpics/《华尔街日报》； ISTOCK (3) <span>Daisy korpics/华尔街日报；艾斯托克 (3)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091608"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091608"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/julie-wernau" itemprop="url" rel="author">朱莉·韦尔瑙</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 10:55 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/synthetic-alcohol-no-hangover-511fc418"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>如果您可以尽情享受您最喜欢的鸡尾酒而不会出现宿醉或其他不良影响，该怎么办？</p><p>这是研究人员努力减少世界上最古老的恶习之一危害的目标之一。有些人正在开发激素注射剂来帮助人们快速清醒。其他人正在研究酒精替代品，其目标是大脑中影响幸福感的受体，同时避开那些让饮酒者含糊不清和编织的东西。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “酒精就像戴着拳击手套弹钢琴。你敲的键太多了，”GABA 实验室董事总经理 David Orren 说道。</p><p>这家总部位于伦敦的公司正在开发一种合成酒精，据称这种酒精可以带来愉悦的效果，并且不会出现宿醉、健康问题或言语不清的情况。它的基础是γ-氨基丁酸，这种氨基酸针对大脑前部的受体，触发酒精带来的放松和社交性，同时避免它对身体造成的混乱。</p><p> GABA 实验室首席科学官 David Nutt 博士表示，他对酒精和 GABA 受体的兴趣始于近 40 年前，当时他的研究使他发现了两者之间的相互作用。作为一名精神病学家和神经精神药理学家，他在美国国立卫生研究院国家酒精滥用和酒精中毒研究所担任了两年临床科学部门负责人，长期以来一直在科学论文中指出，酒精对社会造成的危害比其他药物更大。</p><p>纳特说，GABA 受体是大脑中酒精的第一个接触点，可以让人们敞开心扉并放松。但酒精也会让大脑充满其他神经递质，从而导致严重的后遗症。</p><p>他说，创造一种只针对 GABA 受体的物质可以让大脑在晚上的快乐开始时自然地开启多巴胺和血清素。 “感觉就像一杯酒的感觉。感觉很放松。它让你变得更健谈，更能与人进行社交互动，”他谈到 GABA 实验室正在开发的名为 Alcarelle 的产品时说道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825139?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> GABA 实验室的首席科学官 David Nutt 博士正在致力于开发一种合成酒精。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：CJ莫利</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该公司正在努力筹集约 800 万<em>英镑</em>（约合 1030 万美元），目标是到 2026 年中期在美国完成食品安全测试，并将先于欧洲和英国市场推出。 “现阶段只有发明家才可以使用它，”纳特说。</p><p>奥伦和纳特说，一路上进行了大量的自我测试，在许多早期的迭代中他们没有任何感觉。两人都记得那天他们喝了一杯最新版本的 Alcarelle，并知道他们终于做对了。 “感觉就像温暖的光芒，”奥伦说。 “你就是你。 And you&#39;re being with somebody that&#39;s being them. You&#39;re being real.”</p><p> The company says it has a US partner in place to help find volunteers to test the product, a project manager and has identified a number of laboratories to help produce Alcarelle once the funding is in place.</p><p> As part of the testing, the company will weigh the effects of mixing Alcarelle with real alcohol or using it at excessive amounts, Nutt says.</p><p> The synthetic alcohol is a tasteless ingredient formulated to be added to versions of nonalcoholic drinks from beer to wine and spirits, the inventors say. It could be added to drinks produced without alcohol or those where alcohol has been removed.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> explore the future of everything</h4><p> <em>The Future of Everything looks at the innovation and technology transforming the way we live, work and play, covering <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-ahead-for-work-bd3a352d" target="_blank" class="icon none">the workplace</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-ahead-for-health-5dccbfca" target="_blank" class="icon none">health</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-ahead-for-energy-climate-19d48267" target="_blank" class="icon none">energy &amp; climate</a> and more.</em></p></div></div><p> Some consumers, concerned about <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/alcohol-long-term-health-risks-c6d572d2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">health effects</a> , have moved to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-low-alcohol-cocktails-wine-and-beer-are-on-the-rise-11652272172?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">consume less alcohol</a> in recent years. The isolation of the pandemic contributed to a spike in drinking in 2020, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9897121/#:~:text=The%20proportion%20exceeding%20drinking%20guidelines%20between%20February%20and%20November%202020,stress%2C%20depression%2C%20and%20anxiety." target="_blank" class="icon none">research</a> has shown, but alcohol consumption <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/one-glass-of-wine-a-day-64ead6a9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has since retreated</a> , particularly among younger people. Sales of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-low-alcohol-cocktails-wine-and-beer-are-on-the-rise-11652272172?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">no- and low-alcohol beverages</a> rose in 2022, according to industry tracker IWSR.</p><p> In addition to its addictive properties, alcohol can cause various harmful effects beyond hangover headaches and loss of motor control. With an enzyme called alcohol dehydrogenase, the liver breaks down ethanol into a toxic compound called acetaldehyde, a carcinogen. The National Institutes of Health says the substance contributes to more than 200 health conditions.</p><p> Alcohol can contribute to health problems for anyone, not just people with alcohol-use disorder, says Dr. Joseph Volpicelli, medical director and founder of the Volpicelli Center for Addiction Treatment in Pennsylvania. “Alcohol use is on a spectrum. It&#39;s not a dichotomous condition.”</p><p> Some researchers are working on ways to help people cut back <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/one-glass-of-wine-a-day-64ead6a9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a> on the amount of alcohol they drink.</p><p> Amygdala Neurosciences in San Francisco is developing an oral drug that aims to inhibit alcohol cravings by targeting dopamine pathways that are triggered when people encounter places and people they associate with drinking. Their drug, a small organic molecule, blocks an enzyme that is critical in dopamine pathways. That results in in dopamine becoming a completely different molecule that reduces the production of dopamine, with its pleasurable effects, during a craving. Fewer cravings can help lower drinking to healthier levels, the company says.</p><p> “People who can&#39;t control drinking don&#39;t always want to stop drinking completely,” says Dr. Mack Mitchell, senior medical advisor for Amygdala. “They just want to be able to drink normally.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825358?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Some companies are working on drugs that will lower cravings for alcohol during a big night out.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ISTOCK</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Pharmaceutical company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UK/XLON/INDV" class="company-name">Indivior</a> has completed a clinical trial for a nasal spray people could take before a big night out on the town to make them want to drink less than usual. “I arrive in the parking lot. I don&#39;t want six or seven drinks. I&#39;ll top up with a nasal spray,” says Chief Executive Officer Mark Crossley, laying out a use case for the product.</p><p> The drug, naltrexone, works on opioid receptors in the brain&#39;s reward system and blocks the pleasant effects of alcohol. Indivior wants to make a short-acting version of naltrexone that works within five minutes, says Christian Heidbreder, the company&#39;s chief scientific officer.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What do you think about prospects for a synthetic alcohol that would bring pleasure without the hangover?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> What about when someone drinks too much? Researchers from UT Southwestern Medical Center in Dallas and Howard Hughes Medical Institute at Rockefeller University in March demonstrated that inebriated mice injected with a stress hormone sobered up within one to two hours—more than twice as quickly as inebriated mice without the shot.</p><p> They tested it on inebriated mice that had passed out on their backs. The first time the mice came out of their booze-induced slumber after being injected with the hormone, researchers were shocked. A research assistant at the Dallas laboratory leaped up and declared it a miracle.</p><p> “This is one of those experiments that you never think will work,” says Steven Kliewer, a biologist at UT Southwestern Medical Center and a co-author on <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36889282/" target="_blank" class="icon none">the study</a> published in the journal Cell Metabolism. “It was a career-defining moment.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1360" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/d3a6bd35-cc9a-4030-94b0-3607d01749b5-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The hormone, FGF21, is produced in the liver in response to alcohol. Previous studies showed that it leads mice to drink less alcohol, drink more water and also protects against alcohol-induced injury to the liver. The hormone activates noradrenaline, a neurotransmitter essential to arousal, attention, cognitive function and stress.</p><p> Mice injected with the hormone were also able to walk on a rotating rod—a rodent equivalent of walking a straight line. It&#39;s unclear if the mice had hangovers.</p><p> The idea isn&#39;t for bartenders to have a tool to sober up drunk patrons. Instead, the researchers say they envision selling the treatment as a tool to reverse alcohol poisoning or sober up people in emergency rooms.</p><p> “It would be more harmful than good behind a bar,” Kliewer says.</p><p> Write to Julie Wernau at <a href="mailto:julie.wernau@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">julie.wernau@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d0225ea7-8532-42a1-8c31-5b317282b95d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:55:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/synthetic-alcohol-no-hangover-511fc418</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/synthetic-alcohol-no-hangover-511fc418<author><![CDATA[Julie Wernau]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> wsjhealth</category><category> wsj future of everything</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>WSJ Future of Everything</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kim Jong Un Flaunts North Korea’s Newest Weapons]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>平壤过去通常在有中国和俄罗斯官员在场的阅兵式上表现得更加克制，但现在不再这样了<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093057"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5CF434C5-8D62-429D-BAB3-0599A261F2F3&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fkim-jong-un-flaunts-north-koreas-newest-weapons-with-russia-and-china-by-his-side-125399f5&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">中国和俄罗斯代表团周四参加了平壤举行的阅兵式，这是自Covid-19大流行开始以来首次对朝鲜进行外国访问。 《华尔街日报》的 Dasl Yoon 解释了这三个国家之间不断发展的关系。照片：STR/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093057"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dasl Yoon</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/timothy-w-martin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Timothy W. Martin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 8:26（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-flaunts-north-koreas-newest-weapons-with-russia-and-china-by-his-side-125399f5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>首尔——在俄罗斯国防部长和一名中国政治局委员的陪同下，当朝鲜能够到达美国本土的导弹轰鸣穿过平壤市中心的街道时，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">金正恩</a>微笑着。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-celebrates-major-holiday-with-special-guests-from-china-and-russia-fc3386fc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">周四晚上朝鲜阅兵的</a>场景反映出金正恩的新的虚张声势，这位39岁的独裁者将朝鲜称为核国家。</p><p>在前几年的类似庆祝活动中，当莫斯科和北京官员在场时，平壤<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-cuts-icbms-out-of-military-parade-1536477004?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">就减弱了核火力的展示</a>，或者冒着惹怒其两个盟友的风险，这两个盟友可以在联合国安理会投票支持新的制裁。</p><p>但最近，这三个国家因对美国及其盟友的共同不满而团结在一起。近年来，朝鲜进行了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-launches-suspected-long-range-missile-4fcd270f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">数十次非法导弹试验</a>，尽管中国和俄罗斯一再阻止追究金氏政权责任的努力。</p><p> “现在，不再有这样的沉默寡言了，”卡内基国际和平基金会核政策项目斯坦顿高级研究员安基特·潘达说。 “金正恩公开展示朝鲜不断增长的能力，并得到了莫斯科和北京的默许。”</p><p>朝鲜周四举行阅兵式，庆祝 1950 年至 1953 年朝鲜战争停火协议结束 70 周年。该国展示了其最新的洲际弹道导弹（名为“Hwasong-17”和“Hwasong-18”）以及新型攻击和间谍无人机。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="463" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825574?width=700&amp;height=463" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">平壤举行阅兵庆祝朝鲜战争停火70周年。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：str/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>作为庆祝活动的一部分，金正恩邀请了自大流行以来的第一批外国代表团访问朝鲜，其中俄罗斯代表团由国防部长谢尔盖·绍伊古率领，中国代表团由政治局委员李鸿忠率领。金系着银色领带，身穿黑色西装，坐在绍伊古和李的旁边监督游​​行。但这位第三代朝鲜领导人没有按惯例发表讲话。</p><p>相反，朝鲜国防部长康善南站起来警告该国的对手。据朝鲜官方媒体报道，他说：“现在的问题不是朝鲜半岛是否会发生核战争，而是谁将在何时引发这场核战争。”</p><p>平壤官方媒体称，绍伊古在与金正恩会面时讨论了与朝鲜在国防和安全领域发展“战略和战术合作”。绍伊古还<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-gives-north-korea-reasons-to-draw-closer-to-russia-11661695201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">赞扬朝鲜对俄罗斯“特别军事行动”的“坚定支持</a>”，这是莫斯科通常提到其入侵乌克兰的方式。</p><p>中国现在没有什么动力越过朝鲜，因为美国增加了在该地区的军事存在，而金氏政权的崩溃将在中国边境造成不稳定。但两国经常发生冲突。 2017年，当中国官方媒体对朝鲜大量武器试验表示不满时，平壤指责北京<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-lashes-out-at-china-1493822167?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“跟着美国的节奏跳舞</a>”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=901F4C0B-AEB7-4EE0-90AB-3AAD0B945CAA&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fkim-jong-un-flaunts-north-koreas-newest-weapons-with-russia-and-china-by-his-side-125399f5&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">朝鲜媒体显示，领导人金正恩带着俄罗斯国防部长谢尔盖·绍伊古参观了一个装满武器的大厅，包括导弹和无人机。此次活动正值俄罗斯和中国代表团访问该国，庆祝朝鲜战争武装冲突结束 70 周年。照片：法新社照片/朝中社 VIA KNS<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>朝鲜正遭受<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-suffers-one-of-its-worst-food-crises-in-decades-ee25aa86?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">几十年来最严重的粮食短缺之一</a>，其经济因对 Covid-19 的担忧而持续实施的制裁和边境限制而受到严重打击。该国的武器成就是金正恩可以自豪地吹捧的少数几个领域之一。</p><p>周五发表的官方媒体报道强调，朝鲜在打击“帝国主义战争狂人”（指的是美国）后增强了其军事能力。军事关系。</p><p>平壤观察人士表示，俄罗斯和中国代表团出席阅兵有助于朝鲜证明其武器扩张的合理性，因为这两个盟友为金氏政权提供了经济命脉和政治支持。</p><p> 2021 年 1 月，金正恩给出了一份异常详细的武器路线图，作为新五年战略的一部分。 Roughly halfway in, North Korea has tested many of the new technologies and rolled them out for Thursday&#39;s parade, such as its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-threatens-radioactive-tsunami-with-new-underwater-drone-d82e2f6e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">underwater drone</a> and nuclear-capable <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-gives-biden-a-missile-testa-new-but-familiar-hello-11616682497?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">short-range ballistic missiles</a> .</p><p> Two new drones were revealed for the first time on Wednesday at a weapons exhibition Kim and Shoigu visited. At the parade the next day, one of the new models was showcased during the procession of the country&#39;s weaponry. North Korea hasn&#39;t publicly named either drone yet, though they are nearly identical visually to the US-made MQ-9 Reaper drone and the RQ-4 Global Hawk, weapons experts said.</p><p> Despite visual similarities, the North Korean drones still lack key technology such as sensors and avionic systems that are necessary for deployment, said Yang Uk, a military analyst at the Asan Institute for Policy Studies in Seoul. “They want to appear as if they are on schedule to develop new weapons but we won&#39;t know until the systems are tested,” Yang said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="465" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825575?width=700&amp;height=465" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> North Korea showcased its newest intercontinental ballistic missiles as well as new attack and spy drones during the parade.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：str/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Kim&#39;s five-year weapons strategy focuses on drones, tactical nuclear arms and other modern advances, as well as a push into cyber, said Kim Young-jun, who advises the South Korean government on national-security issues. That brings advantages because these areas are often less costly and more efficient than conventional military capabilities—all the more important now given North Korea&#39;s economic struggles, he added.</p><p> “I am surprised by the pace of North Korean development—more rapid than I would have guessed,” said Bruce Bennett, senior defense analyst at Rand Corp., a think tank based in Santa Monica, Calif. “The North&#39;s transparency is intended to support its objective of demonstrating superiority.”</p><p> Write to Dasl Yoon at <a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com</a> and Timothy W. Martin at <a href="mailto:Timothy.Martin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Timothy.Martin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 12:26:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-flaunts-north-koreas-newest-weapons-with-russia-and-china-by-his-side-125399f5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-flaunts-north-koreas-newest-weapons-with-russia-and-china-by-his-side-125399f5<author><![CDATA[Dasl YoonTimothy W. Martin]]></author><category> wsjworld</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Kim Jong Un</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Economic Cost of Houston’s Heat: ‘I Don’t Want to Be Here Anymore’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> If the weather pattern continues through August, Texas&#39; gross state product will be reduced by roughly $9.5 billion, according to an economist <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824344/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="在德克萨斯州东南部发布高温警告期间，可以看到休斯顿市中心的天际线。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The skyline of downtown Houston is seen during excessive heat warnings for Southeast Texas. GO NAKAMURA/REUTERS <span>GO NAKAMURA/REUTERS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086980"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086980"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-wolfe" itemprop="url" rel="author">Rachel Wolfe</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/amara-omeokwe" itemprop="url" rel="author">Amara Omeokwe</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 8:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-dont-want-to-be-here-anymore-the-economic-cost-of-houstons-heat-3cf69016"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> HOUSTON—Houstonians pride themselves on how they tolerate heat. This summer, the heat has become intolerable.</p><p> Businesses and residents in America&#39;s fourth-largest city have moved much of life indoors, changing work and spending habits. Some residents say they are reminded of quarantining during the pandemic&#39;s early days: ordering in groceries, avoiding social commitments and looking for ways to stay entertained from the couch.</p><p> The result is a dent to the local economy that could become an annual pattern if <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">summers stay hotter for longer.</a></p><p> “This year is different, people are staying home,” said Barbara Stewart, a professor of human development and consumer sciences at the University of Houston. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824345?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An unrelenting heat wave in Texas is testing the state&#39;s power grid as demand soars during a second week of triple-digit temperatures.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: DAVID J. PHILLIP/ASSOCIATED PRESS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> At Buffalo Bayou Brewing, a taproom and restaurant in the Heights neighborhood, fewer people are coming to the restaurant <strong>&nbsp;</strong> during the day, said Jonathan Horowitz, chief revenue and strategy officer. Earlier this month, the restaurant purchased two new portable cooling units to put behind the rooftop deck&#39;s bar to better keep staff cool.</p><p> He estimates revenue during the heat wave is down roughly 10% compared with the same time in 2022.</p><p> “It seems like the time frame of this kind of heat has expanded beyond what it used to be,” Horowitz said. “We always had 100-degree days, but when you have 100-degree days for two months straight, that&#39;s different.”</p><p> Employees at small- and medium-size businesses in the tourism, arts and entertainment and sports and recreation industries in Texas averaged 19.6 hours on the job a week between mid-June and mid-July, a 20% decline from the average during comparable weeks from 2019 to 2022, according to an <a href="https://gusto.com/company-news/working-hours-drop-as-temperatures-rise-nationwide" target="_blank" class="icon none">analysis</a> from Luke Pardue, an economist at payroll platform Gusto. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1AED9094-3E0F-4B58-802C-EF73D149AAC5&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fi-dont-want-to-be-here-anymore-the-economic-cost-of-houstons-heat-3cf69016&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> As extreme temperatures strain electric grids in the US, many parts of the country could face blackouts. Solar energy can help protect the grid during extreme heat, but it comes with the added cost of increasing climate waste and decreasing efficiency. Photo illustration: Xingpei Shen<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>If the weather pattern so far this summer continues through August, Texas&#39; gross state product this year <strong>&nbsp;</strong> will be reduced by roughly $9.5 billion, making a small dent in the state&#39;s growth rate, according to Ray Perryman,</p> an economist and president at the economic research and analysis firm the Perryman Group. That estimate assumes average temperatures in the state this summer will be roughly 2.6 degrees above the long-term average since 1900, Perryman said.<p></p><p> Samuel Westry, a real-estate agent in the greater Houston area, said some of his clients have been reluctant to attend property showings in person. Technology, such as virtual visits, have helped business continue, but it is harder to get people to buy without a face-to-face visit, he said.</p><p> The weather has also made it tough to look presentable.</p><p> “God forbid the air conditioner is out at a house that I&#39;m showing or the electricity is off,” he joked, adding that he has been keeping an emergency towel and deodorant in the car.</p><p> Darrell Ard owns the West Montgomery Auto Repair shop in the Northside neighborhood. He said he has been slammed with Freon top-offs and air-conditioner repairs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824343?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Darrell Ard said more people are coming to his auto repair shop for Freon top-offs and air-conditioner repairs.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Rachel Wolfe/The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> While many of his customers previously put off the expense of a fix for weeks or months to save up, “now they&#39;re going to jump right on it,” said Ard, who started the business five years ago.</p><p> <a href="https://www.richmondfed.org/-/media/RichmondFedOrg/publications/research/economic_brief/2018/pdf/eb_18-08.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">A 2019 research paper</a> found that, on average, each one-degree Fahrenheit increase in the mean summer temperature in the US leads to a 0.154 percentage-point decrease in the annual growth rate of gross state product. The decline is roughly double in Southern states, such as Texas, said Bridget Hoffmann, an economist at the Inter-American Development Bank and one of the paper&#39;s co-authors.</p><p> Hoffmann and co-authors also found that higher summer temperatures negatively affect output growth in a range of industries, including agriculture, construction, finance and insurance, while boosting it in the utilities and mining industries.</p><p> The negative impact shows that “moving towards a service economy and moving some of your economy out of agriculture isn&#39;t enough to insulate your economy,” Hoffmann said.</p><p> The Houston Health Department has given out air conditioners and set up manned cooling centers so people without air conditioning can take refuge from the heat. Danny Perez, a spokesman for the Texas Department of Transportation, said the heat had caused two road buckles and some pavement failures in the Houston area. The cost to the state to repair the road buckles totaled roughly $400,000, according to data provided by Perez. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824348?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Construction workers rebuild the I-69 Southwest/I-610 West Loop Interchange during a heat wave in Houston.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: MARK FELIX/AGENCE FRANCE-PRESSE/GETTY</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Electric Reliability Council of Texas, which manages the state&#39;s electrical grid and in recent years <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/texas-power-grid-was-minutes-from-collapse-during-freeze-operator-says-11614202063?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">struggled to perform during severe weather events</a> , said peak energy demand has reached new highs five times so far this summer. Most recently, peak demand reached 82,592 megawatts on July 18, compared with the record before this summer of 80,148 megawatts in July 2022.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>If you&#39;re in Houston or another city affected by this summer&#39;s heat, how are you coping?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> At Aire Serv of River Oaks, co-owner Hector Jimenez said service requests are up about 12% from this time last year. “We&#39;re stretched to capacity,” he said.</p><p> The company has struggled to retain technicians as the prospect of working in blistering sun and 110-degree-plus attics <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/plumbers-contractors-demand-25ff0036?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">collides with a shortage of skilled workers</a> .</p><p> Repairs can run from a few hundred to a few thousand dollars, while new HVAC systems retail from $7,900 all the way to $18,000-plus. Across the US, HVAC repairs are 28% more expensive on average as of last month than they were in June 2021, rising to $1,401, according to data from management software firm Jobber. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/00f7141e-f4d2-4bc0-9c97-2df0b0b265b3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Miguel Jimenez, whose parents own Aire Serv, said he is working 10- to 12-hour days with few days off. “A lot of people are counting on me,” he said.</p><p> On a recent Thursday in the East End neighborhood, the younger Jimenez fixed a leaking unit for the Blanding family, who was hunkered down in the living room with the curtains drawn.</p><p> “I usually enjoy the quiet and stillness of summer, but I don&#39;t want to be here anymore,” said Benjamin Blanding, a 42-year-old math professor at San Jacinto College, who grew up just outside the city.</p><p> The family postponed a coming vacation to Goose Island State Park when they saw the heat index would reach 108 degrees. And they bailed on a visit to the public pool after less than an hour when the water felt hotter than the air. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824342?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Blanding family, Benjamin, Leila and Soraya, postponed a vacation because of the extreme heat.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Rachel Wolfe/The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Eleven-year-old Leila Blanding, who spent that morning reading, said she misses being able to go down to the bayou by the house and out skateboarding with her friends. “It can get boring,” she said.</p><p> After delivering the Blandings their $600 bill, Jimenez hopped back in the car for a quick unit tuneup at an Airbnb where Alvin Moore was staying. A lifelong Southerner, the 27-year-old Moore had planned to spend his time in Houston enjoying the golf courses and soccer fields.</p><p> Lately, he has been hard-pressed to find anyone willing to play.</p><p> “The course is mostly empty,” he said.</p><p> Write to Rachel Wolfe at <a href="mailto:rachel.wolfe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rachel.wolfe@wsj.com</a> and Amara Omeokwe at <a href="mailto:amara.omeokwe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">amara.omeokwe@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-dont-want-to-be-here-anymore-the-economic-cost-of-houstons-heat-3cf69016</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-dont-want-to-be-here-anymore-the-economic-cost-of-houstons-heat-3cf69016<author><![CDATA[Rachel WolfeAmara Omeokwe]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category> Economic Performance/Indicators</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Environmental Health</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>Natural Environment</category><category> Global/World Issues</category><category> Health</category><category> Weather</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> economic performance</category><category> indicators</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>environmental health</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>climate change</category><category> natural environment</category><category> global</category><category> world issues</category><category> health</category><category> weather </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Bank of Japan Hints It Will Accept Higher Rates, Lifting Bond Yields]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Analysts see move toward eventual rate increases, though BOJ Gov. Ueda says monetary easing remains in place <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001092536"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825540?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> BOJ Gov. Kazuo Ueda has said the bank would refrain from making any premature rate increases.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Dhiraj Singh/Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001092536"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/megumi-fujikawa" itemprop="url" rel="author">Megumi Fujikawa</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 28, 2023 7:49 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-japan-bucking-speculation-keeps-main-policy-unchanged-8d79ab6b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> TOKYO—The countdown is beginning toward the end of the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JP/XTKS/8301" class="">Bank of Japan</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> decadelong radical monetary easing, although markets are divided about how many ticks are left on the clock.</p><p> The central bank on Friday let the yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond rise to a nearly nine-year high, and Gov. Kazuo Ueda said he was giving the market more freedom to push yields higher.</p><p> But Ueda said the move didn&#39;t mean the bank was giving up on the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-worlds-most-radical-experiment-in-monetary-policy-isnt-working-1488135495?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">monetary easing pursued over a decade</a> by his predecessor, Haruhiko Kuroda. Policies under Kuroda included a negative short-term interest rate and large purchases of government bonds to keep the 10-year bond yield tightly capped, most recently at 0.5%.</p><p> The bank said Friday that <a href="https://www.boj.or.jp/en/mopo/mpmdeci/mpr_2023/k230728a.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">the 0.5% cap is now a suggestion</a> , not a rigid limit, and it set a new rigid limit at 1%. Soon after, the yield on the 10-year JGBs briefly hit 0.575%, the highest level since September 2014, before it fell back to 0.54%.</p><p> Japan&#39;s interest-rate moves <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-the-bank-of-japans-shift-could-play-out-in-u-s-markets-b5d7acf5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">matter for US markets</a> because Japanese financial institutions are major investors in US government and corporate bonds. Rising interest rates in Japan could lead some of them to try to bring their money back home, influencing US bond markets and pushing down the dollar against the yen. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="760" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826235?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Ueda said the new policy was aimed at “improving the sustainability of the framework” of monetary easing. He said he didn&#39;t think the new 1% boundary would be reached, calling it a “just-in-case cap.”</p><p> But he also characterized the greater flexibility as a hedge against risks, suggesting it could be helpful if <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/japan-inflation-hits-four-decade-high-pressuring-central-bank-in-2023-11671791596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">inflation</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-japan-needs-more-confidence-inflation-will-stay-high-to-change-policy-ueda-says-4b1b7a16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">keeps</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/japan-inflation-hits-four-decade-high-pressuring-central-bank-in-2023-11671791596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">surpassing expectations</a> . Inflation has been running above 3%, above the Bank of Japan&#39;s 2% target, and the BOJ raised its forecast for inflation this fiscal year, admitting its April forecast missed the durability of price rises in Japan.</p><p> Market players said Ueda&#39;s tolerance of higher rates and allusions by the bank to inflation risks suggested further steps were likely over the next year, such as ending negative short-term rates or eliminating the bond-yield cap.</p><p> If so, Japan would be following belatedly on the path traveled since last year <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">by the Federal Reserve</a> and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ecb-rate-decision-july-83e574cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">European Central Bank</a> , both of which have steadily raised their benchmark interest rates to fight inflation.</p><p> JPMorgan economist Ayako Fujita said she had considered an end to negative rates a less-likely scenario over the next year but now believes “the possibility has heightened considerably” of it happening next spring.</p><p> BNP Paribas economist Ryutaro Kono said he saw the bank&#39;s greater flexibility announced Friday as “preparation for upward pressure on long-term yields when the BOJ abolishes negative interest rates.”</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-28-2023/card/what-could-higher-yields-in-japan-mean-for-global-markets--3Lo857fcscixR5wkuBKQ?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Investors weren&#39;t quite sure</a> what to make of the moves. The Nikkei Stock Average fell sharply in the initial minutes after the BOJ&#39;s announcement, only to recover most of the lost ground and finish down 0.4%.</p><p> The yen initially gained on expectations for higher interest rates—which would make yen—denominated assets more attractive—then gyrated during a news conference by BOJ leader Ueda as he suggested higher rates weren&#39;t imminent.</p><p> Bank shares surged because higher government bond yields mean they can charge higher interest rates on commercial loans and earn better yields from bonds and other investments.</p><p> Japanese exporters such as carmakers have generally profited from the yen&#39;s weakness over the past year, which makes their exports from Japan more competitive in dollar terms. Masahiro Ichikawa, a strategist at Sumitomo Mitsui DS Asset Management, said that so long as rates don&#39;t jump too much, investors should feel at ease about corporate profits.</p><p> “The BOJ is likely to prevent any rapid increases in yields to show that it is not moving toward an exit,” Ichikawa said.</p><p> Weighing the BOJ&#39;s cap on government-bond yields—an unorthodox tool among global central banks—some analysts drew a comparison to the Bank of Japan&#39;s stock-buying program, which has stopped actively making purchases but hasn&#39;t been officially eliminated. Likewise, they said, the yield cap could be gradually abolished de facto even if it technically remains in place.</p><p> — <em>Kosaku Narioka contributed to this article.</em></p><p> Write to Megumi Fujikawa at <a href="mailto:megumi.fujikawa@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">megumi.fujikawa@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 11:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-japan-bucking-speculation-keeps-main-policy-unchanged-8d79ab6b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-of-japan-bucking-speculation-keeps-main-policy-unchanged-8d79ab6b<author><![CDATA[Megumi Fujikawa]]></author><category> wsjworld</category><category>银行业</category><category>中央银行业务</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>金融服务</category><category>货币政策</category><category>央行干预</category><category>Interest Rates</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>债务/债券市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>政府债务/债券市场</category><category>国家政府债务/债券市场</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>日本银行</category><category>8301.TO</category><category>邮编：8301</category><category> Kazuo Ueda</category><category>货币政策</category><category>央行干预</category><category>interest rates</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>债务</category><category>债券市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>政府债务</category><category>国家政府债务</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</ca